# Code Conventions — MERN + TypeScript

## General
- TypeScript strict mode — no `any`, use proper types or generics
- Use `const` by default, `let` only when reassignment is needed
- Prefer `async/await` over `.then()` chains
- Always handle errors explicitly — no silent catches
- Keep functions small and single-purpose

## Naming
- Components: `PascalCase` (e.g. `UserCard.tsx`)
- Hooks: `camelCase` prefixed with `use` (e.g. `useAuthUser.ts`)
- Utils / helpers: `camelCase` (e.g. `formatDate.ts`)
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
- Types / Interfaces: `PascalCase`, prefix interfaces with `I` only if ambiguous
- MongoDB models: singular `PascalCase` (e.g. `User`, `Listing`)
- API routes: `kebab-case` (e.g. `/api/bus-listings`)

## File & Folder Structure
```
src/
├── components/       # Reusable React components
├── pages/            # Route-level components
├── hooks/            # Custom React hooks
├── services/         # API call functions (axios/fetch wrappers)
├── models/           # Mongoose models
├── routes/           # Express route handlers
├── controllers/      # Business logic, called by routes
├── middleware/        # Express middleware
├── utils/            # Pure utility functions
├── types/            # Shared TypeScript types/interfaces
└── config/           # Environment config, constants
```

## React
- Functional components only — no class components
- Props via TypeScript interfaces, defined above the component
- Avoid prop drilling beyond 2 levels — use context or state manager
- Co-locate styles with components when using CSS modules

## Node / Express
- Controllers handle logic, routes just wire them up
- Validate all inputs at the route level (zod or express-validator)
- Return consistent API response shapes:
```ts
{ success: boolean, data?: T, error?: string, message?: string }
```

## MongoDB / Mongoose
- Always define schemas with explicit types
- Use `lean()` for read-only queries
- Index fields used in frequent queries

## Imports
- Use absolute imports via `tsconfig` path aliases (e.g. `@/components/Button`)
- Group imports: 1) Node built-ins, 2) External packages, 3) Internal modules
